# Memory guardrails (Shipwright)

## Fail-closed enforcement (A1)

Three layers — do not conflate them:

| Layer | What | Greenfield (zero memories) |
| --- | --- | --- |
| **Static** | `.cursor/rules/sw-guardrails.mdc` (`alwaysApply`) | Always on — baseline plugin guardrails without Recallium |
| **Dynamic** | Rule-class memories from the provider, filtered by allowlist | Empty is **normal** for a new repo / new `memory.project` |
| **Hook** | `beforeSubmitPrompt` fail-closed check | Blocks only when the provider is **unreachable** (cannot confirm state) |

Repos **without** `workflow.config.json` are not gated (global plugin install must not block unrelated workspaces).

When opted in (`workflow.config.json` present) and `memory.guardrails.enforceBeforeSubmit` is true (default):

- Provider unreachable → **block** (A1 / R44 — cannot confirm guardrail state).
- Provider reachable, zero rule-class memories → **pass** (confirmed empty; not a failure).
- `memory.guardrails.requireRuleClass: true` → **block** until at least one allowlisted rule-class memory exists (strict / mature repos only).

Set `memory.guardrails.enforceBeforeSubmit: false` to disable the hook entirely (plugin development, temporary bypass).

`sessionStart` injection is best-effort (fail-open).

## Planning store memory backend (PRD 034 R11/R25)

The `planning.store` memory backend routes exclusively through the provider-agnostic memory adapter and
`scripts/memory-redact.py` on both read and write. It never calls provider MCP tools directly, bans
`discussion`/`progress` classes for planning bodies, and refuses raw transcript content.

## Redaction chokepoint (R41)

Before any memory persist or re-injection, run the shared redaction filter on:

- transcript deltas (`/sw-memory-sync`)
- deploy-log edges (deferred workstream)
- Sentry payload edges (deferred workstream)

Named patterns: AWS `AKIA…`, `ghp_…`/PATs, JWTs, `Bearer` headers, PEM private keys, email addresses.

## Rule-class promotion (R42)

`category: rule` requires human confirmation + provenance metadata. Auto-distilled candidates cannot
promote without `/sw-memory-audit` approval. Active rules must appear in `.cursor/sw-memory-rule-allowlist.json`.

## Trust boundary (R43)

Memory provider holds project-scoped operational data. Least-privilege API credentials via environment only.
Compromised provider → rotate credentials, audit allowlist, re-export neutral JSONL.

## Source of truth — decision class (PRD 015)

`memory.sourceOfTruth` (`repo` | `memory` | `auto`, default `auto`) selects which side is authoritative for
**frozen decision records** only. Other memory categories remain distillation-only.

| Effective SoT | Authoritative | Non-authoritative |
| --- | --- | --- |
| `repo` (default `auto`+in-repo) | git decision record | provider pointer via `relatedFiles` |
| `memory` | provider `decision` record (redacted) | committed git snapshot pointer |

Resolve via `python3 scripts/memory-sot.py resolve --class decision --json`. Switching modes requires an
explicit operator change plus `/sw-memory-audit` + `memory-sot-audit.py legacy-reconcile-plan`. Redaction
(R41) and rule-class gates (R42) apply identically in both modes.
